One small correction to your understanding

You said:

"FFT's high amplitude at a certain frequency is considered as target?"

A more precise statement is:

A peak in the FFT indicates a strong reflection at a particular beat frequency. That beat frequency is converted into a range. It becomes a candidate target, and then additional processing (CFAR, Doppler, angle estimation, and tracking) decides whether it is a real object or just noise or clutter.

This distinction is important because not every strong FFT peak corresponds to a real target. Radar DSP uses several stages to reject false detections before reporting an object.

